<item>How are colds transmitted?</item>
<item>What is responsible for the symptoms of a cold?</item>
</list>
</note>
<note id="fs-id1167663557379" class="microbiology clinical-focus">
<title>Part 3</title>
<para id="fs-id1167663587077">Since antibiotic treatment had proven ineffective, John’s doctor suspects that a viral or fungal pathogen may be the culprit behind John’s case of pneumonia. Another possibility is that John could have an antibiotic-resistant bacterial infection that will require a different antibiotic or combination of antibiotics to clear.</para>
<para id="fs-id1167663633120">The RIDT tests both came back negative for type A and type B influenza. However, the diagnostic laboratory identified the sputum isolate as <emphasis effect="italics">Legionella pneumophila</emphasis>. The doctor ordered tests of John’s urine and, on the second day after his admission, results of an enzyme immunoassay (EIA) were positive for the <emphasis effect="italics">Legionella</emphasis> antigen. John’s doctor added levofloxacin to his antibiotic therapy and continued to monitor him. The doctor also began to ask John where he had been over the past 10 to 14 days.</para>
<list id="fs-id1167663635259" list-type="bulleted" bullet-style="bullet">
<item>Do negative RIDT results absolutely rule out influenza virus as the etiologic agent? Why or why not?</item>
<item>What is John’s prognosis?</item>
</list>
